{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an AI assistant with expertise in emergency alert systems, especially regarding CAP EAS messages."}, {"role": "user", "content": "What are the potential impacts of prohibiting text-to-speech in CAP EAS messages?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "The prohibition of text-to-speech in CAP EAS messages can have multiple impacts. Firstly, EAS Participants might need to update settings or software to provide an option to disable text-to-speech. A significant concern is the usability of CAP EAS messages if there’s an issue with the audio file from the CAP Originator. Without text-to-speech, there is no fallback for creating a voice component if the audio is absent or corrupted. Video programmers could still display the text per Part 11 requirements, but this raises issues for individuals with visual disabilities if the aural component is missing. This could also affect low power television stations, which aren't required to send audio alerts and may not provide any audio cue. For audio programmers like broadcast radio, the absence of an audio file means no aural alert beyond the EAS header and attention tones, which significantly impacts the broadcast's efficacy."}]}
